observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendations that the City Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to complete the inventory count to facilitate the reconciliation of the results of the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE), pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
b. Property Officer/GSO to maintain PCs and immediately record the property being delivered upon acceptance and inspection, pursuant to Section 119 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I; and necessary changes for the accounting of property;
c. OIC-City Accountant to complete the reconciliation of the PPELCs, and ensure that the balances reflected in the ledger cards reconcile with the balances per books at any given time. Gather all supporting documents to record all property which were included in the RPCPPE but not recorded in the books of accounts;
d. OIC-City Accountant to prepare lapsing schedule of all depreciable property; and regularly check that all items listed in the ledger cards have complete details, such as date of purchase/completion. Prepare journal entry to adjust the depreciation expense if details of all necessary; and
e. Accountable Officers and other concerned officers/personnel to determine the cause of the delay in the submission of the request for relief from accountability and make the necessary action to submit the same.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
a. OIC-City Accountant to send collection letters to the borrowers and the cooperatives, and to the concerned employees for the deduction to be made in the payroll; and provide the Human Resource Office the list of the concerned employees for the deduction of overpayment to be made in the payroll;
b. City official concerned to request the COA an authority to write-off the long outstanding/dormant balances of accounts, if all collection efforts have been exhausted, and the possibility of collecting the amount due from dissolved NGOs is deemed nil, following the guidelines set for the proper disposition of the same under COA Circular No. 97-001 dated February 5, 1997 and COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
c. OIC-City Accountant to exert effort in establishing the details of dishonored checks which were recorded under Other Receivables account; and
d. OIC-City Accountant, focal persons and other concerned officials to strictly follow the terms and conditions stated in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) or contract whenever funds were released as loan assistance.

We reiterated our recommendations that the City Mayor direct the:

Inventory Committee to complete the inventory count to prove existence of the City’s properties, and to submit the required report thereon to the Auditor, pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS, Volume I.  Also, the inventory report should be reconciled with the Accounting and Property records. Any discrepancies found should be investigated, and the necessary adjustments should be made where the error was committed;

Office of the City Accountant to continue exerting efforts in tracing back prior years’ acquisition of Property, Plant and Equipment to have a complete detail of the fixed asset accounts so that  the  corresponding depreciation could be computed, to present fairly the true value of the depreciable fixed asset accounts;

accountable officers of the lost/destroyed properties to submit immediately to the Auditor the request for relief from property accountability, duly supported with all the required documentations, so that they can be relieved from any liability, and the cost of the items could be dropped from the books of accounts of the City; 

City General Services Office to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIURP), to account for all unserviceable and obsolete items previously taken up in the books as assets, so that they may be properly disposed of and dropped from the accounts. Moreover, the disposal of property shall be made in accordance with COA Circular No. 89-296 dated January 27, 1989; and

Property Officer/GSO to make certain that Property Cards are well-maintained, complete and updated to facilitate the physical count of property and equipment. Determine the officials/employees to whom the equipment were issued, and issue the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) for each property to pinpoint the direct person accountable and responsible thereon.  Moreover, renew all ARE every three years for the signature of the holder of each item listed in the RPCPPE.
